Mennonites - a people at once united by an ethnic and religious identity, yet also shaped by differences in geography, immigration histories, denomination, and class position - provides insights into how and why they have resisted involvement in organized labour. Not Talking Union adds a unique perspective to the history of labour, exploring how people negotiate tensions between their commitments to faith and conscience and the demands of their employment. Not Talking Union breaks new methodological ground in its close analysis of the oral narratives of North American Mennonites. Reflecting on both oral and archival sources, Thiessen shows why Mennonite labour history matters, and reveals the role of power and inequality in that history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLabor unionszCanadaxHistory. 0aLabor unionszCanadaxReligious aspectsxMennonites. 0aLabor unionszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aLabor unionszUnited StatesxReligious aspectsxMennonites. 0aMennoniteszCanadaxAttitudes. 0aMennoniteszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aOral historyzCanada. 0aOral historyzUnited States. 70(DE-601)1045295550(DE-588)4020872-2aGewerkschaft2gnd 70(DE-601)1062224140(DE-588)4040600-3aMündliche Überlieferung2gnd 70(DE-601)1062313080(DE-588)4038633-8aMennoniten2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359894240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773598942423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773598942/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles